13 foll. ‘It was this danger which Regulus had foreseen when he counselled the senate not to ransom himself and his fellow captives.’ The danger which he foresaw was, that if there were the hope of ransom, Roman soldiers would come to prefer captivity to a brave death. Now they had come to acquiesce in it, so much as even to forget their own country.
